@NODE 4 "Reservoir Dogz - Help."
                              @{FG HIGHLIGHT}4. PLAYING THE GAME@{FG TEXT}

  In all reality, playing Reservoir Dogz is very simple. But first, I think
  there are a number of principles you need to understand:-
  
      Gunshot wounds are not easily healed. They are very painful, and
       shooting yourself in the chest is probably not a good idea.
       
      Gravity is everywhere. Your gun hand is not immune to gravity.
       Understand that the crosshair will also succumb to the forces of
       the mighty Isaac Newton.
       
      Policemen in the United Kingdom do not carry guns. Therefore this
       game is not very realistic, as it is set in the UK. However, that
       doesn't mean you can go out and just shoot a copper because he is
       unarmed.
       
      Reservoir Dogz is not really very good. It was just a test to see
       if I could do a game like this.
       
  Anyway, to play Reservoir Dogz, press '1' on the main menu screen.
  (to get to the main menu screen, press the left mouse button whilst the
  credits sequence is displayed, ie when it is first started.) If you leave
  the main menu alone for 10 seconds, the high score table will be
  displayed. If you leave it for a further 10 seconds, then the main menu
  will come back. If you don't want to wait 10 seconds though, just click 
  the left mouse button to get back to the main menu.
  
  The introductory text for level 1 will be 'vidiprinted' on the screen.
  To skip this, press the left mouse button. Then the backdrop will appear
  and so will five other things:-
  
      @{FG HIGHLIGHT}A copper.@{FG TEXT} On level 1, he will appear from one of three different
       places. Get ready to shoot him with the...
       
      @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Crosshair.@{FG TEXT} This is your targeting system. Simply move the crosshair
       over the copper and press the left mouse button to shoot. Note that
       your crosshair is affected by gravity.
       
      @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Ammo Indicator.@{FG TEXT} This shows you how much ammunition you have left in
       the current magazine. You have unlimited magazines, and load
       another magazine, press the @{FG HIGHLIGHT}right mouse button@{FG TEXT}. However, if
       you do this while there are still bullets in the old one, points will
       be lost!
       Each magazine contains a maximum of @{FG HIGHLIGHT}8 rounds@{FG TEXT}.
       
      @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Health Level.@{FG TEXT} This shows how healthy you are. By this I don't mean
       the amount of fresh veg. you have in your diet, but the number of
       times you have been shot, and the maximum hits you can suffer without
       dying.
 
      @{FG HIGHLIGHT}The Score Indicator.@{FG TEXT} Positioned above the health bar, this tells
       you your current score. It doesn't notify you when you qualify for
       high score table name entry.
       
  On level 1, there are @{FG HIGHLIGHT}20 coppers@{FG TEXT} to shoot, but 
  this figure increases, as does their reaction time. Yes, the coppers 
  shoot back. Occasionally, they will actually hit you, and you will lose
  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}10%@{FG TEXT} health. When your health level hits @{FG HIGHLIGHT}
  20%@{FG TEXT} you will die. Whenever you complete a level, your health
  level increases by @{FG HIGHLIGHT}20%@{FG TEXT}. The coppers accuracy
  is increased as you progress through the 5 levels.
  
  There are 5 levels, each with more positions that the coppers can appear,
  more coppers, and a lower reaction time for each copper. There is an end
  sequence, but it isn't more than a static picture with a story on it.

  The scoring system is as follows:

      Every copper killed earns you @{FG HIGHLIGHT}20 points@{FG TEXT}.
     
      Every shot that misses takes @{FG HIGHLIGHT}5 points@{FG TEXT} from your score.

      Every time the coppers hit you, you lose @{FG HIGHLIGHT}1 point@{FG TEXT}.

      If you reload while the magazine is not empty, you lose @{FG HIGHLIGHT}10 points@{FG TEXT}.
 
  When you complete a level, you get a bonus of @{FG HIGHLIGHT}100 points@{FG TEXT}.
  When you complete the game, you get a bonus of @{FG HIGHLIGHT}1000 points@{FG TEXT}.
  If, at the end of the current game, you score was high enough to get on
  to the high score table, you will have the opportunity of entering your
  name. These high scores are kept in the 'R_Dogz.scores' file and are
  saved when you Exit to Workbench from the Main Menu.
   
